blood on his face, shaking a clenched fist and shouting =E2=80=9CFight! Fig=
ht! Fight!=E2=80=9D before being rushed offstage to safety=E2=80=94I realiz=
ed that the question I=E2=80=99d be grappling with in this space was altoge=
ther different: Is this game, set, match?

Of course, there were questions of greater immediate urgency related to the=
 crime itself: Trump=E2=80=99s condition and that of the other victims in B=
utler, the identity and motives of the shooter, and so on. And there were q=
uestions of greater long-term consequence: What effect might this heinous, =
horrific act and the wave of reactions to it=E2=80=94on the right, on the l=
eft, and in the vast, yawning, aching middle of the ideological spectrum=E2=
=80=94bring to bear on a political and civic culture increasingly defined b=
y its turbulence and toxicity, its ever-widening political divisions and ev=
er-fraying bonds of social cohesion, its reflexive blame-casting and persec=
ution-claiming, its downright pathological incapacity to grapple with the
sickness of our gun culture, and, simmering away beneath all of the above, =
its pervasive sense of fear.

