The same can be said of almost all of the potential political implications =
of the attempted Trump assassination. Politico=E2=80=99s Playbook had a goo=
d long list ( https://www.politico.com/newsletters/playbook/2024/07/14/can-=
america-turn-the-temperature-down-00168062?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+=
Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F14%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Br=
ightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F30%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sourc=
e=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) this morning of the looming=
 questions of the post-Butler era: Will MAGA rallies ever be the same? Does=
 this affect Trump=E2=80=99s V.P. calculations? Will Democrats talk differe=
ntly about the stakes of the election, or about Trump=E2=80=99s autocratic =
impulses, authoritarian designs, and democracy-imperiling policy agenda? Ho=
w will this affect Biden=E2=80=99s
tenuous hold on the Democratic nomination and the efforts inside the party =
to induce him to step aside? I could speculate endlessly about all the matt=
ers, but the truth is, less than 24 after those shots rang out in Pennsylva=
nia, it=E2=80=99s simply too soon to make anything approaching an informed =
assessment.

It=E2=80=99s not too soon, however, to discuss the spectacle about to unfol=
d at the Fiserv Forum in Milwaukee. This morning on CNN, my pal David Axelr=
od opined, =E2=80=9CThe president =E2=80=A6 will be greeted as a kind of ma=
rtyr at this event, and I think it could be angrier or could be more somber=
=2E But it=E2=80=99s certainly not goin=
g to be the same.=E2=80=9D I agree tha=
t it=E2=80=99s not going to be the same, but have zero expectation whatsoev=
er that the difference will bend toward the somber. Long before last night,=
 the MAGA-fied G.O.P. viewed Trump as a righteous victim and were all-in on=
 his self-proclaimed agenda of retribution. In Milwaukee, he=E2=80=99ll be =
greeted not only as a
martyr but as something even more mythic: a bona fide hero, a warrior liter=
ally bloodied in battle, and (at least among those who occupy the party=E2=
=80=99s Evangelical pews) maybe even a messiah. It is going to be a sight t=
o see=E2=80=94and not a pretty one, at least for those of us who considered=
 ourselves card-carrying members of Team Democracy.

But it will also be a sight=E2=80=94in combination with the brutal ordeal t=
o which Trump has just been subjected and the undeniable swagger he showed =
off (at least in public) in the heat of the moment=E2=80=94that is all but =
certain to give him a lift with the electorate than he would have otherwise=
 gotten from his party=E2=80=99s primetime shindig in Milwaukee. I asked Mi=
ke Murphy, Axelrod=E2=80=99s cohost on the Hacks on Tap podcast and as arde=
nt a #NeverTrump Republican as exists on planet Earth, how big a bounce in =
the polls he expected Trump to receive from the convention. Murphy, who bel=
ieves that Trump=E2=80=99s raised-fist moment will
be =E2=80=9Cthe iconic symbol=E2=80=9D of the next four days in Brew City, =
replied, =E2=80=9CHe has a ceiling, but this is going to smash him up again=
st it. He=E2=80=99ll have a solid five to six point lead in the swing state=
s, I think, and maybe more.=E2=80=9D

If that=E2=80=99s right=E2=80=94and it seems entirely plausible to me=E2=80=
=94whatever remaining hopes Democratic electeds, donors, and strategists st=
ill harbor about Biden=E2=80=99s ability to stage a heroic comeback are lik=
ely shriveled to the point of vanishing altogether. Which brings us back to=
 Alberta=E2=80=99s Atlantic piece and one passage in particular: =E2=80=9CL=
aCivita had long conceived of the 2024 race as a contest that would be =E2=
=80=98extraordinarily visual=E2=80=99=E2=80=94namely, a contrast of strengt=
h versus weakness. Trump, whatever his countless liabilities as a candidate=
, would be cast as the dauntless and forceful alpha, while Biden would be p=
ainted as the pitiable old heel, less a bad guy than the butt of a very bad=
 joke, America=E2=80=99s lovable but lethargic
uncle who needed, at long last, to be put to bed.=E2=80=9D

In the wake of Biden=E2=80=99s debate debacle, that passage was striking en=
ough, but reading it again in the aftermath of Trump=E2=80=99s brush with d=
eath, it hits you like a two-by-four across your temples. For many, many, m=
any months, the 2024 campaign was a tepid, torpid turnoff, a sequel starrin=
g two senescent retreads that the vast majority of the electorate had preci=
ous little interest in, let alone enthusiasm about. But the seismic events =
of the past fortnight have changed all that. Everyone is watching now, rapt=
=2E The implications for each candid=
ate of what they=E2=80=99re seeing are al=
most too obvious to say out loud.

