          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The same can be sai=
d of almost all of the potential political implications of the attempted Tr=
ump assassination. Politico=E2=80=99s Playbook had a <u><a href=3D"https://=
email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dRdEdMNk5YZlp=
tQkQteWFLM196MD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucG9saXRpY28uY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZX=
JzL3BsYXlib29rLzIwMjQvMDcvMTQvY2FuLWFtZXJpY2EtdHVybi10aGUtdGVtcGVyYXR1cmUtZ=
G93bi0wMDE2ODA2Mj91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStT=
VUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjg3JTJGMTQlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50PVRoZStCZXN0KyU=
yNitUaGUrQnJpZ2h0ZXN0Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4NiUyRjMwJTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG=
1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1d=
G1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEy=
YSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjk1NzMxMX0/edd6f2d05b3c5cd4cf3496f85ca485c33093033989b3ea8=
ad9259041ba15d939" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:=
bold" class=3D"sdf">good long list</a></u> this morning of the looming ques=
tions of the post-Butler era: Will MAGA rallies ever be the same? Does this=
 affect Trump=E2=80=99s V.P. calculations? Will Democrats talk differently =
about the stakes of the election, or about Trump=E2=80=99s autocratic impul=
ses, authoritarian designs, and democracy-imperiling policy agenda? How wil=
l this affect Biden=E2=80=99s
tenuous hold on the Democratic nomination and the efforts inside the party =
to induce him to step aside? I could speculate endlessly about all the matt=
ers, but the truth is, less than 24 after those shots rang out in Pennsylva=
nia, it=E2=80=99s simply too soon to make anything approaching an informed =
assessment.<br/><br/>It=E2=80=99s not too soon, however, to discuss the spe=
ctacle about to unfold at the Fiserv Forum in Milwaukee. This morning on CN=
N, my pal <b>David</b> <b>Axelrod</b> opined, =E2=80=9CThe president =E2=80=
=A6 will be greeted as a kind of martyr at this event, and I think it could=
 be angrier or could be more somber. But it=E2=80=99s certainly not going t=
o be the same.=E2=80=9D I agree that it=E2=80=99s not going to be the same,=
 but have zero expectation whatsoever that the difference will bend toward =
the somber. Long before last night, the MAGA-fied G.O.P. viewed Trump as a =
righteous victim and were all-in on his self-proclaimed agenda of retributi=
on. In Milwaukee, he=E2=80=99ll be greeted not only as a
martyr but as something even more mythic: a bona fide hero, a warrior liter=
ally bloodied in battle, and (at least among those who occupy the party=E2=
=80=99s Evangelical pews) maybe even a messiah. It is going to be a sight t=
o see=E2=80=94and not a pretty one, at least for those of us who considered=
 ourselves card-carrying members of Team Democracy.<br/><br/>But it will al=
so be a sight=E2=80=94in combination with the brutal ordeal to which Trump =
has just been subjected and the undeniable swagger he showed off (at least =
in public) in the heat of the moment=E2=80=94that is all but certain to giv=
e him a lift with the electorate than he would have otherwise gotten from h=
is party=E2=80=99s primetime shindig in Milwaukee. I asked <b>Mike</b> <b>M=
urphy</b>, Axelrod=E2=80=99s cohost on the <i>Hacks on Tap </i>podcast and =
as ardent a #NeverTrump Republican as exists on planet Earth, how big a bou=
nce in the polls he expected Trump to receive from the convention. Murphy, =
who believes that Trump=E2=80=99s raised-fist moment will
be =E2=80=9Cthe iconic symbol=E2=80=9D of the next four days in Brew City, =
replied, =E2=80=9CHe has a ceiling, but this is going to smash him up again=
st it. He=E2=80=99ll have a solid five to six point lead in the swing state=
s, I think, and maybe more.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>If that=E2=80=99s right=E2=
=80=94and it seems entirely plausible to me=E2=80=94whatever remaining hope=
s Democratic electeds, donors, and strategists still harbor about Biden=E2=
=80=99s ability to stage a heroic comeback are likely shriveled to the poin=
t of vanishing altogether. Which brings us back to Alberta=E2=80=99s <i>Atl=
antic</i> piece and one passage in particular: =E2=80=9CLaCivita had long c=
onceived of the 2024 race as a contest that would be =E2=80=98extraordinari=
ly visual=E2=80=99=E2=80=94namely, a contrast of strength versus weakness. =
Trump, whatever his countless liabilities as a candidate, would be cast as =
the dauntless and forceful alpha, while Biden would be painted as the pitia=
ble old heel, less a bad guy than the butt of a very bad joke, America=E2=
=80=99s lovable but lethargic
uncle who needed, at long last, to be put to bed.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>In the =
wake of Biden=E2=80=99s debate debacle, that passage was striking enough, b=
ut reading it again in the aftermath of Trump=E2=80=99s brush with death, i=
t hits you like a two-by-four across your temples. For many, many, <i>many =
</i>months, the 2024 campaign was a tepid, torpid turnoff, a sequel starrin=
g two senescent retreads that the vast majority of the electorate had preci=
ous little interest in, let alone enthusiasm about. But the seismic events =
of the past fortnight have changed all that. Everyone is watching now, rapt=
=2E The implications for each candid=
ate of what they=E2=80=99re seeing are al=
most too obvious to say out loud.<br/></td>
